                    <item_0
                        jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                        sling:resourceType="core/franklin/components/block/v1/block/item"
                        model="text-container-text"
                        modelFields="[text]"
                        name="Text Container Text"
                        text="&lt;p>To find the right patients for a specific treatment, AbbVie researchers are using predictive biomarkers and ultimately the companion diagnostic assays which are tests used to help match a patient to a specific drug or therapy. But it all begins with developing a deep understanding of each disease driver, which are mutations that cause tumor growth. “Developing a deep, molecular understanding of disease is highly complex, requiring expertise from across the company,” McCaffery said.&lt;/p>&lt;p>“This means that precision medicine takes a village. It requires clinical and translational scientists working closely with colleagues from other groups in R&amp;#x26;D to bring all the necessary expertise to generate and interpret molecular information. While this complexity can seem daunting, AbbVie has broad and deep expertise across the organization.”&lt;/p>&lt;p>This expertise comes from cutting-edge technologies used to identify predictive markers that build upon our understanding of molecular drivers. For some diseases, especially where phenotypic data are hard to quantify, AbbVie researchers are incorporating digital technologies including sensors, wearables, and other technologies to help identify which patients would benefit most from a treatment, McCaffrey said.&lt;/p>"/>
                </block_3>
